"Rypdal K., Rive N., Berntsen T.K., Klimont Z., Mideksa T.K., Myhre G., Skeie R.B.","Costs and global impacts of black carbon abatement strategies",2009,"Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology","61","4",,"625","641",,,10.1111/j.1600-0889.2009.00430.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70350559033&partnerID=40&md5=ea1a756490055fa00abff231bd3bf017","CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA), A-2361 Laxenburg, Austria","Rypdal, K., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Rive, N., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Berntsen, T.K., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Klimont, Z., International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA), A-2361 Laxenburg, Austria; Mideksa, T.K., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Myhre, G., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway; Skeie, R.B., CICERO, P.O. Box 1129 Blindern, N-0318 Oslo, Norway","Abatement of particulate matter has traditionally been driven by health concerns rather than its role in global warming. Here we assess future abatement strategies in terms of how much they reduce the climate impact of black carbon (BC) and organic carbon (OC) from contained combustion. We develop global scenarios which take into account regional differences in climate impact, costs of abatement and ability to pay, as well as both the direct and indirect (snow-albedo) climate impact of BC and OC. To represent the climate impact, we estimate consistent region-specific values of direct and indirect global warming potential (GWP) and global temperature potential (GTP). The indirect GWP has been estimated using a physical approach and includes the effect of change in albedo from BC deposited on snow. The indirect GWP is highest in the Middle East followed by Russia, Europe and North America, while the total GWP is highest in the Middle East, Africa and South Asia. We conclude that prioritizing emission reductions in Asia represents the most cost-efficient global abatement strategy for BC because Asia is (1) responsible for a large share of total emissions, (2) has lower abatement costs compared to Europe and North America and (3) has large health cobenefits from reduced PM10 emissions. © 2009 The Authors Journal compilation © 2009 Blackwell Munksgaard.",,"abatement cost; black carbon; climate effect; combustion; emission control; global warming; organic carbon; prioritization; Asia",,,,,,"Ackerman, A.S., Toon, O.B., Stevens, D.E., Heymsfield, A.J., Ramanathan, V., Reduction of tropical cloudiness by soot (2000) Science, 288, pp. 1042-1047; Amann, M., Bertok, I., Cofala, J., Gyarfas, F., Heyes, C., (2005) Baseline Scenarios for the Clean Air for Europe (CAFE) Programme-Final Report, , IIASA, Laxenburg, Austria; Barrie, L.A., (1986) Atmos. Environ., 20, pp. 643-663; Berglen, T.F., Berntsen, T.K., Isaksen, I.S.A., Sundet, J.K., A global model of the coupled sulfur/oxidant chemistry in the troposphere: the sulfur cycle (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. D19310. , doi:10.1029/2003JD003948; Berntsen, T., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Global temperature responses to current emissions from the transport sectors (2008) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., 105, pp. 19154-19159; Berntsen, T.K., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Joshi, M., Shine, K.P., Stuber, N., Climate response to regional emissions of ozone precursors; sensitivities andwarming potentials (2005) Tellus, 57 B, pp. 283-304; Berntsen, T., Fuglestvedt, J., Myhre, G., Stordal, F., Berglen, T.F., Abatement of greenhouse gases: does location matter? (2006) Clim. Change, 74, pp. 377-411; Bond, T.C., Sun, H., Can reducing black carbon emissions counteract global warming? (2005) Environ. Sci. Technol., 39, pp. 5921-5926; Bond, T.C., Streets, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S.M., Woo, J.-H., A technology-based global inventory of black and organic carbon emissions from combustion (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. D14203. , do